<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910301-0002</DOCNO><DOCID>910301-0002.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   William Oldenburg   Must Pay Damages   In Utah Thrift Case</HL><DATE>03/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   SALT LAKE CITY -- A federal judge ordered formerhigh-flying loan broker J. William Oldenburg and twoassociates to pay $22 million in damages for defrauding aUtah savings and loan association once controlled by Mr.Oldenburg.   The judge, David K. Winder, also held Mr. Oldenburgindividually liable for $13.7 million of loans made by thethrift, State Savings andamp; Loan Association, Salt Lake City, toother companies controlled by him through his holdingcompany, Investment Mortgage International, San Francisco.Mr. Oldenburg received much publicity in the mid-1980s forhis alleged extravagance, including purchase of thenow-defunct World Football League's Los Angeles Express teamand for the many millions of dollars he spent on his poshheadquarters and parties for thrifts from which he obtainedloans for clients.</LP><TEXT>   The rulings resulted from a lawsuit brought against Mr.Oldenburg in 1985 by the now-defunct Federal Savings and LoanInsurance Corp., after State Savings failed. The otherdefendants are Martin Mandel, an attorney and State Savingsdirector, and Charles Burgardt, another director.   Messrs. Oldenburg and Mandel also face criminal charges ina trial scheduled to begin April 1 in San Francisco.Previously, the two men were tried on nine criminal counts,six of which were dismissed after the jury deadlocked. Theywere also acquitted on two charges and convicted on one countof falsifying financial records. The conviction wasoverturned last year on appeal. Another State Savingsdirector, James W. Rossetti, pleaded guilty to four counts ofconspiracy and bank fraud, and is scheduled to facesentencing in federal court in California.</TEXT></DOC>